SIMPLE: expression
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expression
<hw>Ex*pres"sion</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧ks*pr⟦ecr⟧sh"⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>expressio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>expression</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of expressing; the act of forcing out by
pressure; <as>as, the <ex>expression</ex> of juices or oils</as>; also,
of extorting or eliciting; <as>as, a forcible <ex>expression</ex> of
truth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of declaring or signifying; declaration;
utterance; <as>as, an <ex>expression</ex> of the public
will</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With this tone of philosophy were mingled <qex>expressions</qex>
of sympathy.</q> <rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Lively or vivid representation of meaning,
sentiment, or feeling, etc.; significant and impressive indication,
whether by language, appearance, or gesture; that manner or style which
gives life and suggestive force to ideas and sentiments; <as>as, he
reads with <ex>expression</ex>; her performance on the piano has
<ex>expression</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The imitators of Shakespeare, fixing their attention on his
wonderful power of <qex>expression</qex>, have directed their imitation
to this.</q> <rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which is expressed by a countenance, a posture,
a work of art, etc.; look, as indicative of thought or feeling.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>expression</xex> of an eye.⟦rdquo⟧<-- italics omitted in
quote in orig. --> <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It still wore the majesty of <qex>expression</qex> so conspicuous
in his portraits by the inimitable pencil of Titian.</q>
<rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A form of words in which an idea or sentiment is
conveyed; a mode of speech; a phrase; <as>as, a common
<ex>expression</ex>; an odd <ex>expression</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The representation of any
quantity or relation by appropriate characters or symbols, usually in a
specific order.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Genetics)</fld> <def>the production of products by
a gene that cause the appearance of the corresponding protein or
phenotype; -- of a gene or of an organism with a specific gene; <as>as,
the <ex>expression</ex> the beta-galactosidase positive
phenotype</as>,</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>a combination of characters
linked by operators, occurring as part of the code of a computer
program, which must be evaluated according to the rules of the computer
language in order to produce a resulting value.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note> In most programming languages, (a + b) is an
<ex>expression</ex> indicating simple arithmetic addition, if the
variables a and b are real numbers. Many other types of operation may be
used in programs, and each set of symbols indicating an operation is an
<ex>expression</ex> in that program.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Past expression</b></col>, <col><b>Beyond
expression</b></col></mcol>, <cd>beyond the power of description.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Beyond expression</xex> bright.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expressional</ent>⟦br⟧
